

<section>
  <title>exercises</title>
  <introduction>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute the differential, <m>\d y,</m> for each of the following functions:
          <ul>
            <li>
              <title>(a)</title>
              <p>
                <m>y=\sin(2x)</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <title>(b)</title>
              <p>
                <m>y=\cos(-3x)</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <title>(c)</title>
              <p>
                <m>y=\sin(x)\cos(x)</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <title>(d)</title>
              <p>
                <m>y=\sin^2(x)</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <title>(e)</title>
              <p>
                <m>y=\sin(x^2)</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <title>(f)</title>
              <p>
                <m>y=\cos^2(x)</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <title>(g)</title>
              <p>
                <m>y=\cos(x^2)</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <title>(h)</title>
              <p>
                <m>y=\cos(\sin(x))</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <title>(i)</title>
              <p>
                <m>y=3\sin^2(3x)-3\cos^2(3x)</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <title>(j)</title>
              <p>
                <m>y=\cos(5x^3-2x^2-3x+12)</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <title>(k)</title>
              <p>
                <m>y=\sin^2(7\pi x) + \cos^2(7\pi x)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_diff-other-trig">
    <title>The Derivatives of the Other Trigonometric Functions</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Once the differential of <m>\sin x</m> is known, the differentials of the
        other trigonometric functions are easily computed. Since our current
        goal is simply to develop the tools we will need later we will not
        spend any more time on this than necessary.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <subsubsection>
    <title>The Tangent and Cotangent</title>
    <p>
      Observe that by definition <m>\tan(x)=\frac{\sin x}{\cos x},</m> so it
      seems that the Quotient Rule applies:
      <md>
        <mrow>\d\left(\tan x\right) \amp = \d\left(\frac{\sin x}{\cos x}\right)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{\cos x \d(\sin x)-\sin x\d(\cos x)}{\cos^2x}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{\cos^2 x\d x +\sin^2 x\d x}{\cos^2x}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{\cos^2x}\d x</mrow>
        <intertext>and since <m>\sec x = 1/\cos x</m> we have</intertext>
        <mrow>\dfdx{\left(\tan x\right)}{x} \amp = \sec^2x.</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <problem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the Quotient Rule to show that
          <me>
            \d{(\cot x)} = -\csc^2x\d{x}.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </problem>

    </subsubsection>


    <subsubsection>
    <title>The Secant and Cosecant</title>
    <p>
      Observe that by definition <m>\sec x = \frac{1}{\cos x} = \inverse{(\cos
        x)}.</m> Differentiating, we have
      <md>
        <mrow>\d(\sec x) \amp = \d\inverse{(\cos  x)}.</mrow>
        <intertext>By the Power Rule we have</intertext>
        <mrow>\amp =(-1)(\cos x)^{-2}\d(\cos x),</mrow>
        <intertext>so that</intertext>
        <mrow>\amp = (-1)(\cos x)^{-2}(-\sin x)\d x.</mrow>
        <intertext>Simplifying this gives</intertext>
        <mrow>\d(\sec x) \amp = \frac{\sin x}{\cos^2x}\d x</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{\cos x}\cdot\frac{\sin x}{\cos x}\d x</mrow>
        <intertext>so that, finally we have</intertext>
        <mrow>\dfdx{(\sec x)}{x}   \amp = \sec x\tan x.</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <problem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show by similar means that <m>\dfdx{(\csc x)}{x} = -\csc x\cot x.</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </problem>

    <p>
      So the derivatives of all six trigonometric functions are given
      below. <em>Memorize them!</em>
      <index><main>Differentiation Rules</main><sub>Trig Functions</sub></index>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\dfdx{ (\sin x)}{x} = \cos x</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\dfdx{ (\cos x)}{x} = -\sin x</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\dfdx{ (\tan x)}{x} = \sec^2 x</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\dfdx{ (\cot x)}{x} = -\csc^2 x</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\dfdx{ (\sec x)}{x} = \sec x\tan x</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\dfdx{ (\csc x)}{x} = -\csc x\cot x</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>

    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
</section>

